name: beagle-flutter
description:
Beagle is an open source framework that helps developers implement Server-Driven UI in a cross-platform way.

By using Beagle, developers can:

Rapidly change an application layout, data, navigation flow, or even logic, just by changing code in the backend. Be more independent of mobile stores, like App Store and Play Store, because most changes wonâ€™t need an app update. Have more confidence that applications will behave similarly on different platforms, since code will be shared and standardized between backend and frontend. Easily test new business hypothesis or make live fixes on applications to improve users' experience and receive feedback.

description: Rust Kubernetes client and controller runtime
contribution_justification: https://github.com/kube-rs/kube-rs/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md
license_location_justification: https://github.com/kube-rs/kube-rs/blob/master/LICENSE
floss_license_justification: The Apache-2.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The Apache-2.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification: https://github.com/kube-rs/kube-rs#kube-rs
repo_public_justification: https://github.com/kube-rs/kube-rs.git
repo_track_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made.
repo_interim_justification: Final releases are git tags. All other revisions are considered interim versions, and are publicly accessible.
repo_distributed_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git is distributed.
release_notes_vulns_justification: This is noted in the security policy: https://github.com/kube-rs/kube-rs/blob/master/SECURITY.md#security-advisories
vulnerability_report_response_justificat:
They are noted as "will receive immediate attention", and our average issue response time is <14 days.
https://kube.rs/security/#reporting-a-vulnerability
test_justification:
CI uses standard github actions runners. https://github.com/kube-rs/kube-rs/blob/master/.github/workflows/ci.yml controls it.
Test running described in https://github.com/kube-rs/kube-rs/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#testing
test_invocation_justification:
cargo test runs full test suite (apart from e2e) which is standard for rust.
https://github.com/kube-rs/kube-rs/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#testing
test_policy_justification:
Tests are requested in the pull request template: https://github.com/kube-rs/kube-rs/blob/master/.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md
How and what tests to add are described in https://github.com/kube-rs/kube-rs/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#test-guidelines
warnings_fixed_justification: CI build green and without warnings
warnings_strict_justification: All cargo warnings are must-fix, clippy warnings are either fixed/allowed depending on practicality.
crypto_published_justification: We only use crypographic algorithms and protocols supported by rustls/openssl and Kubernetes.
crypto_call_justification: We defer to rustls/openssl for cryptographic protocols and algorithms.
crypto_floss_justification: Openssl is FLOSS. The optional configuration of ring + rustls + webpki is also FLOSS (but ring + webpki requires some special verification of its ISC style licenses).
crypto_keylength_justification: We only use key lengths set by kubernetes clusters that are additionally allowed in secure versions of our provider libraries for cryptography.
crypto_working_justification: We only use cryptographic algorithms dictated by kubernetes clusters that are additionally available in secure versions of our provider libraries for cryptography.
crypto_pfs_justification: We only use cryptographic algorithms for key exchange as dictated by kubernetes clusters' transport protocols. These algorithms additionally have to be available in secure versions of our provider libraries for cryptographic transport.
crypto_password_storage_justification: We do not provide extra storage, and rely on kubernetes configuration files from secure clusters to use secure auth providers.
crypto_random_justification: We generate a single nonce for Sec-WebSocket-Key using rust::random (rand::rngs::ThreadRng) which implements CryptoRng.
delivery_mitm_justification: We only use transport protocols dictated by kubernetes clusters that are additionally configurable in secure versions of our provider libraries for cryptography.
delivery_unsigned_justification: Oauth relies on kubernetes verifying our signatures, and we communicate over https unless specifically requested to be insecure.
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: cargo audit checks lockfile against rustsec advisory db
static_analysis_fixed_justification:
All audit found issues are either fixed if confirmed.
https://github.com/kube-rs/kube-rs/issues?q=is%3Aissue+is%3Aopen+label%3Asecurity+-label%3Ainvalid
dynamic_analysis_justification: inputs to kube proxy to the kubernetes apiserves, which is fuzzed upstream.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: kube is written in rust and uses forbids unsafe_code - verifiable through cargo geiger
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: test code is behind #[cfg(test)], fuzzing is delegated to upstream.
crypto_weaknesses_justification: We only use cryptographic algorithms dictated by kubernetes clusters that are additionally available in secure versions of our provider libraries for cryptography.
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: CI action is required with required github statuses before merges: https://github.com/kube-rs/kube-rs/actions/workflows/ci.yml
discussion_justification: Github Discussions + Issues.
no_leaked_credentials_justification: All credentials stored as repository / organisation secrets.
hardening_justification:
The project is written using entirely safe rust.
https://github.com/kube-rs/kube-rs/search?q=%23%21%5Bforbid%28unsafe_code%29%5D
crypto_used_network_justification: We use TLS for all communication with the apiserver over HTTPS and secure websockets.
crypto_tls12_justification: The kube client uses TLS via either rustls or openssl.
crypto_certificate_verification_justific: kube-client verifies certificates by default unless the user forces insecure-skip-tls-verify.
crypto_verification_private_justificatio: kube-client verifies certificates by default unless the user forces insecure-skip-tls-verify.
hardened_site_justification: https://github.com/kube-rs/ is hardened as GitHub meets this.
installation_common_justification: installable from cargo add or adding one line to Cargo.toml
build_reproducible_justification: rust does not support fully reproducible builds
access_continuity_justification: main maintainers are owners of org, and are members of publish team of crates.io. additionally CNCF ensures continuity of ownership, and they have owners of the org which is part of the CNCF github enterprise: https://github.com/kube-rs
bus_factor_justification: We only have 3 maintainers at the moment, things would clearly slow down if 2 disappeared.
documentation_security_justification:
Does not cover all of these bits yet:
https://github.com/kube-rs/kube-rs/blob/master/SECURITY.md
documentation_quick_start_justification: No official quick start guide, but we are a library with many uses. There is a multitude of examples catering to most user needs instead.
documentation_current_justification: documentation built from current version on release via rustdoc
accessibility_best_practices_justificati: We are a library. We use tracing levels, error enums, and otherwise have our documentation available on popular sites such as github and crates.io.
internationalization_justification: Software does not generate text intended for end-users and doesn't sort human-human readable text.
sites_password_security_justification: users authenticate through github for everything
maintenance_or_update_justification: docs.rs/kube is browsable by version, and https://github.com/kube-rs/kube-rs/blob/master/CHANGELOG.md will inform what the key breaking changes are
coding_standards_enforced_justification: cargo fmt enforces the style on ci
build_preserve_debug_justification: debug symbols are configurable at users request through Cargo.toml - no special action taken by kube-rs.
build_non_recursive_justification: not applicable. we have a folder per crate, and they are built in the deterministic order the acyclic dependency tree creates.
build_repeatable_justification: rust does not support bit-for-bit reproducible builds: https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/75362
installation_standard_variables_justific: Not applicable. Rust has its own system for storing build artifacts.
installation_development_quick_justifica:
Creating a k3d cluster for is documented in https://github.com/kube-rs/kube-rs/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#testing
Additional tooling are also mentioned in the contributing guide.
updateable_reused_components_justificati: cargo upgrade --all can be used to quickly upgrade a dependency everywhere
interfaces_current_justification: We stay up-to-date with dependency using dependabot
automated_integration_testing_justificat: Most of https://github.com/kube-rs/kube-rs/blob/master/.github/workflows/ci.yml must pass before merging
implement_secure_design_justification: The client is secure, denies-by-default, secure-by-default.
input_validation_justification: Data received from Kubernetes must match the typed structs, but  the library does is otherwise not responsible for handling user data.
crypto_algorithm_agility_justification: We support the cryptographic algorithms supported in the intersection of (Kubernetes AND (openssl XOR rustls)).
crypto_credential_agility_justification: Authentication credentials are stored in kubeconfigs which are replaceable without code recompilation, and can refer to cryptographic keys by file references from these configs.
signed_releases_justification: Releases are only published to crates.io using its process for publishing requiring membership in the kube-rs release team.
version_tags_signed_justification: We currently do not sign tags.
copyright_per_file_justification:
This is a developer turn-off. We follow the IP policies set by CNCF.
https://github.com/cncf/foundation/blob/main/copyright-notices.md#copyright-notices
license_per_file_justification:
This do not do this. We follow the IP policies set by CNCF.
https://github.com/cncf/foundation/blob/main/copyright-notices.md#copyright-notices
small_tasks_justification: https://github.com/kube-rs/kube-rs/issues?q=is%3Aissue+is%3Aopen+label%3A%22good+first+issue%22 which github highlights for new contributors
secure_2FA_justification: github does not support disallowing SMS based 2FA
code_review_standards_justification:
Only partially covered at the moment. Key documents are:
https://github.com/kube-rs/kube-rs/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md
https://raw.githubusercontent.com/kube-rs/kube-rs/master/.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md
two_person_review_justification: code review required from another maintainer
assurance_case_justification: There is no such document currently.

name: trousseau
description: Store and Access your Secrets the Kubernetes native way with any external KMS.
description_good_justification:
Once deployed, Trousseau will enable seamless secret management using the native Kubernetes API and kubectl CLI usage while leveraging an existing Key Management Service (KMS) provider.
How? By using using the Kubernetes KMS provider framework to provide an envelop encryption scheme to encrypt secrets on the fly.
